<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND REVIEWS / MUSIC; FISCHER LEADS STYLISH RIDE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIEL CARIAGA, TIMES MUSIC WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Genuine stylishness in musical performances grows more obsolescent with the 
passing seasons -- conductorial expertise apparently having joined the 
endangered species list. When stylishness appears, then, as it did on the final 
program by the touring Budapest Festival Orchestra at Hollywood Bowl, flares 
should be raised. 
</P>
<P>
 Ivan Fischer, co-founder and principal conductor of the ensemble, led this 
agenda (given Friday and Saturday nights), titled "From Budapest to Vienna," 
and offering music by Johann Strauss Jr., Bartok, Lehar, Kodaly, Brahms and 
Berlioz. In all that he surveyed, Fischer seemed master of this territory. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite somewhat less than immaculate performances from the orchestra on 
Friday, the music-making gave consistent pleasure. 
</P>
<P>
 One had forgotten just how wondrous "An der schonen blauen Donau" ("On the 
Beautiful Blue Danube") can be, when taken at tempos that breathe as well as 
sweep. There were also myriad joys in four of Strauss Jr.'s treasurable polkas 
-- "Eljen a Magyar," "Vergnugungszug," "Im Krapfenwaldl" (with all the 
birdcalls) and "Unter Donner und Blitz" -- all of which were appreciated loudly 
by 14,227 Bowl-goers on Friday -- the crowd on Saturday was counted at 
capacity: 17,797. 
</P>
<P>
 One had not forgotten the deep charms of both the "Fledermaus" Overture and 
Berlioz's Hungarian March from "La Damnation de Faust." Fischer brought fresh 
life to them, and the Bowl Fireworks Department lit up the skies colorfully 
during the latter, to enthusiastic cheering. 
</P>
<P>
 The appearance of American soprano June Anderson was disappointing only in 
that she offered merely five items total. 
</P>
<P>
 But these she sang handsomely, though warming up completely only by the final 
"Vilja-Lied" from "Die lustige Witwe." Otherwise, these were pleasant, usually 
effortless run-throughs of excerpts from "Der Zarewitsch," "Zigeunerliebe" and 
"Paganini," plus the "Fledermaus" Czardas. In all of them, Fischer & Co. proved 
sensitive and intrepid collaborators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
