<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHLAND PREVIEW / THE BUSINESS WEEK AHEAD: SAN DIEGO COUNTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Afternoon Edition Dies: The San Diego Union-Tribune today halts publication of 
its afternoon edition, the last vestige of the old San Diego Tribune, which 
owner Copley Newspapers merged with the San Diego Union in 1992. Copley Editor 
in Chief Herb G. Klein said the closing of the once-popular edition, which 
carried closing stock prices and was dubbed the "green sheet" because of its 
green newsprint, reflects a national trend of diminishing popularity of 
afternoon newspapers.Home delivery of the late edition had declined to 65,000 
from more than 100,000 before the merger. Nevertheless, Klein said the 
Union-Tribune's daily circulation of 365,000 is up from the 350,000 papers sold 
five years ago by the Union and Tribune combined. On Sundays, the Union-Tribune 
sells 450,000 copies. No editorial employees were laid off, but eight or nine 
circulation employees will lose their jobs or be converted to part-timers as a 
result of the edition's demise, Klein said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
